HEADWORD: Sidle
<hw>Si"dle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Sidled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Sidling</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[From
<er>Side</er>.]</ety> <def>To go or move with one side foremost; to move
sidewise; <as>as, to <ex>sidle</ex> through a crowd or narrow
opening</as>.</def> <rj><au>Swift.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He . . . then <qex>sidled</qex> close to the astonished girl.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir W. Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Siege</ent>⟦br⟧
